07025nam a22008895i 9780823292363DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20222011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232923637 a10.1515/97808232923632doi  a(DE-B1597)566117  a(OCoLC)1306540979  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0670002bisacsh00aPlanetary Loves :bSpivak, Postcoloniality, and Theology /ced. by Mayra Rivera, Stephen D. Moore. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (440 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransdisciplinary Theological Colloquia00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroductions -- tA Tentative Topography of Postcolonial Theology -- tSituating Spivak -- tWhat Has Love to Do with It? Planetarity, Feminism, and Theology -- tThe Love We Cannot Not Want: A Response to Kwok Pui-lan -- tConversations -- tLove: A Conversation -- tThe Pterodactyl in the Margins: Detranscendentalizing Postcolonial Theology -- tLost in Translation? Tracing Linguistic and Economic Transactions in Three Texts -- tGhostly Encounters: Spirits, Memory, and the Holy Ghost -- tExtempore Response to Susan Abraham, Tat-siong Benny Liew, and Mayra Rivera -- tAppropriations -- tPlanetary Subjects after the Death of Geography -- tLove’s Multiplicity: Jeong and Spivak’s Notes toward Planetary Love -- tNot Quite Not Agents of Oppression: Liberative Praxis for North American White Women -- tPlanetary Sightings? Negotiating Sexual Differences in Globalization’s Shadow -- t‘‘Effects of Grace’’: Detranscendentalizing -- tComparative Theology after ‘‘Religion’’ -- tToward a Cosmopolitan Theology: Constructing Public Theology from the Future -- tPax Terra and Other Utopias? Planetarity, Cosmopolitanism, and the Kingdom of God -- tCrip/tography: Of Karma and Cosmopolis -- tNOTES -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX OF NAMES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPostcolonial theology has recently emerged as a site of intense intellectual and political energy and has taken its place in the interdisciplinary field of postcolonial studies. This volume is animated by the conviction that postcolonial theology is now ready for a second, deeper phase of engagement with postcolonial theory, one that moves beyond the general to the specific. No critic has been more emblematic of the challenging and contested field of postcolonial theory than Gayatri Chakravorty Spivak. In this volume, the product of a theological colloquium in which Spivak herself participated, theologians and biblical scholars engage with her thought in order to catalyze a diverse range of original theological and exegetical projects. The volume opens with a "topography" of postcolonial theology and also includes other valuable introductory essays. At the center of the collection are transcriptions of two extended public dialogues with Spivak on theology and religion in general. A further dozen essays appropriate Spivak's work for theological and ethical reflection. The volume is also significant for the larger field of postcolonial studies in that it is the first to focus centrally on Spivak's immensely suggestive and vital concept of "planetarity."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / General.2bisacsh1 aAbraham, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmour, Ellen T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBetcher, Sharon V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoh, W. Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Serene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct